<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Definitions</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Class Trait - Defining characteristic of a class. This is something the class does extremely well, something unique that sets it apart from other classes of similar background. While other classes may dabble in this field, none surpass it.<br>
<br>
Class Role - This is a maleable thing. A role depends ever so much on circumstance, on area, on your foe, on numerous other things. Rarely is this role ever so simple as to pin it down, especially in the realm of casting classes.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Typical Role</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> A major role of Magicians should be dealing damage.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
In most situations, this is certainly true. We do not have many defensive spells, we do not have shielding, we do not have much utility of mention to a standard experience group. A majority of our spells are tailored specifically to dealing damage, and our primary spell set summons a creature that excels in combat.<br>
<br>
However, I disagree that this role is what Magicians <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> should</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> necessarily have. Granted, it is something we do well, and something we can adapt to over the long haul. With our relative weakness defensively, at best what we magicians have to offer, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> typically</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, is damage.<br>
<br>
We magicians do deal quite a bit of damage, but understand, that a lot of it can be considered indirect damage. We currently have 3 methods of dealing damage to creatures:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Pets</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - Generally a source of pure melee damage, with a handfull of spells thrown in for uniqueness and added damage output.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Spells</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - Our source for magical damage. Often times, in this world of Verant's, magic is null and void, due to level, due to resists, due to immunities, or many other reasons.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Damage Shields</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - A source of much indirect damage. A well placed damage shield can net much more damage over time than spell casting can. This is due to the shield's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> unresistable</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> nature.<br>
<br>
Now, granted, some classes also have damage shields comperable to ours (druids and their 25 point group DS at level 60, or their 32 point single target DS earlier (still after we recieve our 33 point DS)), our damage shield is by far the most potent there is out there. To add to that, with the inclusion of neat little items in Luclin such as a certain dirk (DS called Unity of Fire, a nice 35 point single target DS), it widens the gap a touch between Druid Damage shields and Magician damage shields.<br>
<br>
These are ways we can deal damage to others.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Alternate Roles</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
While it is true that other classes recieve spell lines such as Malo much sooner than we, it is also a fair certainty that these classes already have much to do, especially when engaged in combat. A single slow from a shaman is likely to place that character at the very top of the mob's hate list, and remain so for a while until the main tank can regain control. I cannot tell you how many times on raids I have watched a shaman simply slow a mob, and instantly be summoned. Tack on Debuffing too, also high taunt, and you're almost asking for these classes to sacrifice themselves every time.<br>
<br>
What a Magician can do is aid these other classes out by freeing them of the need to expend their limited mana pool on such troublesome things as resistance debuffs and damage shields. Pair a magician and a shaman together for debuffing, and stripping down in pairs, Mala + Malosini, one can land, with better effectiveness, a debuff to help other casters out. Now, in a way, you could consider every point of damage done by another caster that was permitted <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> meerly</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by the fact that the magician had lowered the mobs resistances a credit to the mage, as well as a credit to the person who cast the spell.<br>
<br>
Also, while many are loathe to admit it, never underestimate the power of free (beer) mana. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  In a raid's downtime, a magician can provide mana in the form of Modulating Rods and Transvergence Rods. Hand everyone in the raid one of each kind, and the mana pool of every caster just got larger. It comes at a price, a sacrifice of hitpoints, but in raid situations, hitpoints are high and risk to casters is generally kept as low as possible. For every drop of mana a Magician can enable another casting class to use is more damage that can be accumulated over time. Again, while each class that does the damage (or allows more damage to be absorbed/caused through healing) should gain credit for their contribution, the Magician <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> also</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> recieves credit because of their ability to enable that extension.<br>
<br>
Much the same argument as immediately prior can be used on the benefit of a magician's summoned resist gear. The more they resist because of that gear, the more damage can be done, the less damage absorbed, and the better off the entire raid is.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Class Clarification</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Since damage was foremost in the argument for pet strength, I'd like to bring up Rogues for a moment.<br>
<br>
Rogues, as a class trait, are damage dealers to the extreme. Through stealth, through trained skill and honed practice and 'optimal conditions', a rogue is a true damage dealer. This is something they do obscenely well, and under the right circumstances, even go so far as to outright kill their foes before they know what hit them. No other class compares to a rogue's power in dealing damage.<br>
<br>
Due to a severe lack of utility and diversification, a Rogue is limited in what they can do. They can scout, this is true. They can clear a path through traps, should there be any in the way. They can open doors not otherwise reachable. However, when it comes down to a rogue's role in a group, be it raid or experience, they can only deal damage, and do so in direct combat with their foe.<br>
<br>
As I've stated before on other threads, and as I shall restate here, a Magician's primary, class defining trait is the fact that they summon and conjure. This is what makes them unique in the world of Norrath. Why is this important, you may ask? It is important because our role BEGINS with our class traits, and works out from there.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Conclusions</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The life of a Magician is far more than meerly dealing damage. While it is something we are very good at in earlier levels, it is primarily because we have very few usefull items or abilities to offer beyond our strong and worthy companion. As we grow in power and strength, we learn to work with more powerfull spells, and summon more powerfull artifacts. Once these artifacts actually gain usefullness to others (Starting with the Shard of the Core in places, Modulating Rods in others, and even occasionally Swords of Runes), then we are asked for them, and we can put these to use unlike our prior summons before.<br>
<br>
As a consiquence, the usefullness of our favored companions, the Elementals, decreases. While I can agree that the decrease does not outweigh the benefits we are offered instead, the overbearing view of Magicians as Damage Dealers <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> alone</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, at least in a direct respect (through use of pets or spells), is overrated.<br>
<br>
I can agree with some thoughts to properly balance our ability to deal damage in line with higher level equipped PC's, I have found that in some cases, the damage caused by a pet in raid situations is not minimal, as some would have it be believed.<br>
<br>
To make a short example before I wrap up, a raid I was on in the Plane of Air sat upon Island 5, the Spirocs. Having cleared every other one off except the Lord himself, we took him on. This Spiroc Lord is no small potato. To me, a level 56 Magician, he was red. Likely, at least level 60 or slightly above. Being as he is, and resistant to all spells I could cast, I took up the role of chain casting pets, as well as damage shielding the melees.<br>
<br>
While I can understand our tank's poor damage output (very small, on the fight I did parse), he was assuming a defensive stance, and working on absorbing damage, not dealing it. As for the others, and as for my pet, I can only say that hands down, my pets (usually 2, sometimes 3) put forth more damage than any melee. Now, it's quite likely that this was because Mobs ignore pets in melee, the Spiroc Lord has a Death Touch, and loves to kill PC's within range with it. Many Melee simply could not last long enough to deal out an obscene ammount of damage. The list of warriors included some with their epic weapons, and others as tough as they could make it. Now, none of us were dressed up in nice fancy NToV gear, but that breaks into another can of worms. Through my damage shield, my ability to meerly Stay Alive and continue to pummel the living daylights out of this Lord through my &quot;substandard&quot; Vocerate Air pet proved well enough to me what kind of role I can play, at least damage wise.<br>
<br>
Though I am of agreement too that some changes to the post-50 pets would be nice. A list of minor changes that I wouldn't mind seeing (and possibly not be overpowering) follows:<br>
<br>
-Alter Voc and GVoc pet spells to be procs instead of spell casts. Voc pets should proc moderately, and the GVoc pets should proc slightly more often.<br>
<br>
-Addition of Focus Items that are reachable (Hi Magi :P) or questable (without giving up a portion of the epic as well) that improve a pet's level or stats would be good. These quests should be hard, perhaps even into the planes still. Currently, no mage I am aware of post-50 wields a single one of their post-50 Foci, wereas every mage pre-50 (just about) wielded theirs.<br>
<br>
-A set of Rage style pets for use on raids would be a very welcome addition. Simple rules apply for these. Direct LoS pathing to target, higher level, same max damage as Rage pets, same low hitpoints, quick attack speed, and elemental style immunity. These spells should drop out of places similar to NToV gear. IE: NToV. (Swords are a warrior's weapon. Pets are ours). These pets would also, by default, operate on the basis of Pet Hold. No other mob would change their focus from their target, though with such low hitpoints, one swipe from an add would render said pet useless anyways. These pets could not tank, making them useless outside of raids, and with a long 5 minute refresh timer, prove less than usefull to experience groups. These pets would be superior to the epic <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> only in so far as damage output is concerned</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
I would be content to see changes such as these three above, and reevaluate pet damage after such changes were made. The procing alone would enable a pet to continue meleeing and not slump off to cast. <p><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=52886">Rhasin Firestorm</A><BR>
